701765f-a.text:
Sedgwick Ave., east side, south from its junction with Undercliff Ave., to West 170th Street (High Bridge), showing W.P.A. men erecting the Sedgwick Ave. Wall.

September 2, 1936.

Works Progress Administration.
Federal Art Project Photo.

701770f-a.text:
Sedgwick Avenue, east side, at Undercliff Avenue, showing the wall erected by the Works Progress Administration, which separates the two thoroughfares. Undercliff Avenue, ascends
the incline on the far side of the wall.
Jan. 13, 1937
W.P.A. Photo
Five Boroughs Project
(2)
The same, some days later.
Jan. 26, 1937
W.P.A. Photo

700855f-b.text:
Depot Place, north side, between Sedgwick Ave and the Harlem River, showing the Highbridge Station of the New York Central Railroad.  The view is southeast-ward across the station and Depot Place and shows an automobile parking space on the east side of the tracks.

June 20, 1940

P. L. Sperr

(2)

East across the auto parking space, Sedgwick Avenue and apartment houses in the W. 167th Street district.  Both views are fromt he Bronx end of High Bridge

June 20, 1940

P. L. Sperr
